    "body": "This behaviour is by design. \r\n\r\nThere are complexities involved with discovery, which are not very well documented which makes this asymmetric behaviour between tcp and udp reasonable (in my opinion). \r\n\r\nSetting the `--enr-address` has a very limited use-case, its primarily used for boot-nodes so that you can construct an ENR that other's can connect to. It really shouldn't be used for a regular client. When creating boot-nodes, because ENR's are somewhat opaque, it has often been the case that user's have set `--enr-address` without setting the `--enr-udp-port` and end up having non-contactable ENR's when setting up boot-nodes. Because of this, we now require the `--enr-udp-port` flag to be set if you are setting the `--enr-address`. This forces you to manually create a contactable ENR for a bootnode. \r\n\r\nNow ENR's can have optional UDP and TCP ports. It can be the case a user wants to have no TCP and no UDP. So defaulting to these ports limits the optionality of having this configuration (this is why we do not default to the udp port). A boot-node does not require TCP, so a bootnode can run happily with a misconfigured TCP port but it cannot function without a UDP port (this is where the asymmetry comes in). \r\n\r\nLighthouse has a `boot_node` CLI command which allows you set up such bootnodes without the TCP option. The TCP port indicates that you have libp2p running and are contactable via the standard libp2p protocols. If you run a beacon node (and therefore construct a listening TCP port) we default to the standard TCP (as we optimistically assume you want your node contacted via TCP on libp2p ports). If you don't explicitly specify an external TCP port, we default to the internal one with no loss to the functionality of the discovery bootnode you have constructed. \r\n\r\nThe reason `--enr-address` should not be used for normal operation, is that if you are behind a NAT, your external ENR address will start off as `None` and remain in this state. This indicates you are not-contactable and should prevent your ENR from being included in the global DHT (as other nodes cannot contact you). If you are behind a NAT and you specify an `--enr-address` and an `--enr-udp-port` this will create an ENR that says you are contactable at these addresses (even though you are not (because of the NAT)). This will make it difficult for other nodes to filter you out of the DHT and will end up polluting it with non-contactable nodes. \r\nIf you are not behind a NAT, the normal operation of the node will start with the external ip of the ENR as None. As it finds nodes and as those nodes can contact you, it will automatically update your ENR to your contactable address. This will then be inserted into the larger DHT correctly. \r\n\r\nSo in short, you shouldn't use `--enr-address` unless you are setting up a bootnode. In which case you must specify your external udp port and optionally set your external tcp port. If you don't want to set your external tcp port, use the `boot_node` cli param which will not start a beacon-node or any libp2p service. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
