    "body": "I realise I didn't answer your question. \r\n\r\n`--enr-address` does what you expect. It will advertise your external IP address. It should be coupled with `--enr-udp-port`, to make sure discovery works. \r\n\r\nFor Lighthouse, you can set these if you know their values. However there is a chance you misconfigure it, and if you are contactable on these addresses, Lighthouse will automatically set the values for you (so in this sense, its a superfluous flag). \r\n\r\nThe one catch is the TCP port. If you have a port-forward, where your external TCP port is different from your internal one, discovery will not update this and you should use the `--enr-tcp-port` to advertise your external TCP port. The main reason is that discovery is UDP based and cannot detect your external TCP port. \r\n\r\nLighthouse is adding UPnP support very soon, which (if supported by your router) will set up the port forwards automatically for you. \r\n\r\nIf you are not contactable, you can still participate in the network, it just means others won't discover and connect to you. I think it's more important that we don't pollute the DHT, than optimistically allowing users to try and manually configure their settings to make them contactable (which isn't a requirement to participate, although it does strengthen the network). ",
